commit_list.message:
attempt to avoid js library conflicts.

a number of other javascript libraries (e.g. prototype and mootools)
also make use of $ as a shortcut alias. calling noConflict() after
jQuery is (hopefully) loaded should eliminate most of these, but
won't address the case where we have a page that uses a very old
version of jQuery. this can be worked around as well but requires
that we produce our own jQuery build using a reasonably unique
global identifier (i.e. not jQuery or $).

commit_list.message:
Clean up relationship types

Removes use of respond_to? in favor of explicit relationship types. i.e. if we say `attributes :foo_ids`, we explicitly intend to only call `object.foo_ids`, not `object.foo.map(&:id)` or equivalent. if you don't specify a relationship in this way, it is probably a good idea to preload associations to avoid N+1s

commit_list.message:
[DOCUMENTATION] Make Sinatra example a bit more secure

I know it's just an example and that real code should have more
checking, but people often copy examples verbatim and I wouldn't
want to read a blog post in the future about this cool trick that
lets you read arbitrary redis keys for most apps deployed via
ember-cli-deploy.

The current example allows users to view any key in redis by
passing an appropriate index_key parameter. This is obviously not
desirable. The amendment I propose isn't 100% secure--it's still
possible to read information that happens to have the same prefix
as the manifest. Ideally one would additionally check to see if
the provided index_key existed in the revisions list before
serving it.

While I could update the example to do this check as well, I worry
that doing so would make the example significantly more complicated
and would obscure what is going on.

Allow itemViewClass to be set for collections in the #collection helper

don't coerce null or undefined in string and integer
attr transforms

getDestFilePath should return null for directories matching extensions

In practice, most directories do not have extensions and as such return
null when passed to getDestFilePath in a filter with extensions
provided. This is important because canProcessFile by default uses this
to determine whether a node should be processed. However, in the case
where a directory happens to have a matched extension (e.g. the tree
contains loader.js/loader.js and we are doing some processing on js
files), we only want the loader.js file, and not the loader.js
directory, to be processed.
Add failing tests that specify getDestFilePath behavior for directories
Fixing typos
Consistently use `this.store` over `this.get('store')` in guides

Don't recommend preloading in ApplicationRoute#activate

model hooks for all routes run before any of the activate hooks.
Consequently this preload code only runs after all of the
required models are requested.
